1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,000
Vancouver Court Hotel. How may I help you?

2
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Hello Vancouver. This is Michael Scott calling from the United States of America.

3
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:14,000
I have a reservation in your fair city from February 12th to the 19th, first week of the Olympics.

4
00:00:14,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Well, we're looking forward to having you, so let me just pull up your information here.

5
00:00:17,000 --> 00:00:18,000
Okeydoke.

6
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:21,000
Is there a unique spelling of your name?

7
00:00:21,000 --> 00:00:25,000
Yes. It is M-I-C-H-A-E-L.

8
00:00:25,000 --> 00:00:28,000
Right. I don't seem to have it, sir.

9
00:00:28,000 --> 00:00:29,000
What?

10
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:36,000
I love the Winter Olympics. My favorite sport is one involving men with brooms.

11
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:43,000
And they broom the ice in front of these cylindrical discs that float gently across the ice.

12
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:50,000
And they smack into one another. And no one really explains the rules, but it's mesmerizing.

13
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:55,000
And there are no winners and no losers. Only poetry.

14
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,000
And it is called curdling.

15
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:03,000
I'm not seeing anything under confirmation. Could it be under affirmation? You have thousands of those.

16
00:01:03,000 --> 00:01:05,000
No, we're just trying to look it up right now.

17
00:01:05,000 --> 00:01:07,000
You did get the e-vite to my barbecue.

18
00:01:07,000 --> 00:01:08,000
Michael?

19
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:15,000
Sir, a lot of people are trying to get last minute reservations at hotels here for the Olympics, but we've been fully booked for months.

20
00:01:15,000 --> 00:01:19,000
Well, I have been booked for three years, so you should have that.

21
00:01:19,000 --> 00:01:24,000
I have always heard that British Columbia is a very nice place, but I'm not getting that from this conversation.

22
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:29,000
Got it. Confirmation code. X-V-2-R-D-M.

23
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:31,000
Oh. Here it is.

24
00:01:31,000 --> 00:01:32,000
Oh.

25
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:33,000
Yeah. Uh-huh.

26
00:01:33,000 --> 00:01:34,000
Thank you.

27
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:35,000
Seven nights in our Street View economy single.

28
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:36,000
That's it?

29
00:01:36,000 --> 00:01:39,000
Yeah. We changed systems a while back. I do apologize.

30
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:41,000
Uh-huh. Okay.

31
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:42,000
How may I help you, Mr. Scott?

32
00:01:42,000 --> 00:01:46,000
All right. I would like to cancel my reservation, please.

33
00:01:46,000 --> 00:01:48,000
There is a cancellation fee for this, sir.

34
00:01:48,000 --> 00:01:50,000
Okay. Put it on my card.

35
00:01:54,000 --> 00:02:16,000
Today, Joe Bennett, the CEO from Sabre, is coming to see us here for the first time.

36
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:20,000
She bought us sight unseen, like a mail-order bride, so she's going to be kind of nervous.

37
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:21,720
So she's got to be kind of nervous.

38
00:02:21,720 --> 00:02:23,180
I mean, are we ugly?

39
00:02:23,180 --> 00:02:24,240
Are we smart?

40
00:02:24,240 --> 00:02:25,120
Are we cool?

41
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:26,280
Are we too cool?

42
00:02:26,280 --> 00:02:27,400
Do we speak English?

43
00:02:32,880 --> 00:02:35,280
Why, hello.

44
00:02:35,280 --> 00:02:37,240
This is Michael Scott, co-regional manager

45
00:02:37,240 --> 00:02:37,960
of this branch.

46
00:02:37,960 --> 00:02:39,400
Pleasure to meet you, Miss Bennett.

47
00:02:39,400 --> 00:02:40,880
That's Mrs. Bennett, sweetheart.

48
00:02:40,880 --> 00:02:43,200
My husband and I are divorced, but I kept the Mrs.

49
00:02:43,200 --> 00:02:45,680
Just to piss off the new wife.

50
00:02:45,680 --> 00:02:47,680
Well, let's take a gander around this place.

51
00:02:47,680 --> 00:02:49,920
These sure are pretty dogs.

52
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:50,960
They love a good garage.

53
00:02:50,960 --> 00:02:52,760
Yeah, they sure do.

54
00:02:52,760 --> 00:02:54,320
You should take that as a compliment.

55
00:02:54,320 --> 00:02:55,080
Oh, I do.

56
00:02:58,320 --> 00:02:59,360
Hello.

57
00:02:59,360 --> 00:03:00,160
Hello.

58
00:03:00,160 --> 00:03:02,760
Do you always stay seated when a lady enters the room?

59
00:03:02,760 --> 00:03:05,060
I am treating you the same as a man for whom I would also not

60
00:03:05,060 --> 00:03:10,240
stand, unless it was the president or Judge Judy.

61
00:03:10,240 --> 00:03:11,900
I like that.

62
00:03:11,900 --> 00:03:12,800
This is accounting.

63
00:03:12,800 --> 00:03:13,300
Uh-huh.

64
00:03:13,300 --> 00:03:14,400
Hi.

65
00:03:14,400 --> 00:03:15,640
Good looking group.

66
00:03:15,640 --> 00:03:18,080
Over here is Meredith Palmer, Creed Bratton.

67
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:19,720
Another couple of heartbreakers.

68
00:03:19,720 --> 00:03:21,320
Who's this tall rink of sun tea?

69
00:03:21,320 --> 00:03:22,320
That is Jim Halpert.

70
00:03:22,320 --> 00:03:24,880
He is the co-regional manager of this office.

71
00:03:24,880 --> 00:03:26,480
I thought this guy was the manager.

72
00:03:26,480 --> 00:03:26,980
Oh, he is.

73
00:03:26,980 --> 00:03:28,400
He's the co-manager there.

74
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:29,440
That's the other co-manager.

75
00:03:29,440 --> 00:03:32,360
Two guys doing one job?

76
00:03:32,360 --> 00:03:33,680
We got to do something about that.

77
00:03:36,960 --> 00:03:41,440
Got some Valentine's cards for my coworkers and my bro workers.

78
00:03:41,440 --> 00:03:42,080
No.

79
00:03:42,080 --> 00:03:42,960
No.

80
00:03:42,960 --> 00:03:43,460
What?

81
00:03:43,460 --> 00:03:44,560
No candy?

82
00:03:44,560 --> 00:03:46,280
Valentine's Day, right around the corner.

83
00:03:46,280 --> 00:03:49,280
Erin and I have been on zero dates.

84
00:03:49,320 --> 00:03:51,160
So I got her a Valentine's Day card.

85
00:03:51,160 --> 00:03:53,360
But I didn't want to seem too eager,

86
00:03:53,360 --> 00:03:55,440
so I got cards for everyone in the whole office

87
00:03:55,440 --> 00:03:57,520
to kind of dilute it a little bit.

88
00:03:57,520 --> 00:03:58,440
Look alive.

89
00:03:58,440 --> 00:03:59,680
Ow!

90
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:02,080
She used to give me a paper cut on my throat.

91
00:04:02,080 --> 00:04:04,560
Yeah, I have this thing about men cutting or threatening

92
00:04:04,560 --> 00:04:05,960
to cut my throat.

93
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:08,080
Don't try to cut my throat.

94
00:04:08,080 --> 00:04:10,680
You know, I get why you guys want to share a job.

95
00:04:10,680 --> 00:04:13,960
You look real good standing there next to each other.

96
00:04:13,960 --> 00:04:14,600
I mean it.

97
00:04:14,600 --> 00:04:16,840
I mean, look, you're tall and thin,

98
00:04:16,840 --> 00:04:18,800
and you're solid and dark.

99
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:20,160
Have a seat.

100
00:04:20,160 --> 00:04:21,520
All right.

101
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:24,640
So it is OK to keep doing the co-manager thing then?

102
00:04:24,640 --> 00:04:25,840
No, that's ridiculous.

103
00:04:25,840 --> 00:04:26,440
OK.

104
00:04:26,440 --> 00:04:28,120
I don't know how things work in Florida,

105
00:04:28,120 --> 00:04:29,800
which from your description sounds

106
00:04:29,800 --> 00:04:32,520
like a colorful lawless swamp.

107
00:04:32,520 --> 00:04:36,800
But here, it takes two men to do one job,

108
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:39,960
where in Florida, it might take one very strong woman

109
00:04:39,960 --> 00:04:41,160
to do such a job.

110
00:04:41,160 --> 00:04:42,160
Whoa.

111
00:04:42,160 --> 00:04:44,800
I'll take over.

112
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:47,720
What we're doing here, Michael handles more of the big picture

113
00:04:47,720 --> 00:04:48,220
stuff.

114
00:04:48,220 --> 00:04:50,900
And I handle more of the day-to-day stuff.

115
00:04:50,900 --> 00:04:52,020
So together.

116
00:04:52,020 --> 00:04:53,820
I think I understand.

117
00:04:53,820 --> 00:04:56,260
Each of you is doing half a job.

118
00:04:56,260 --> 00:04:58,740
Sometimes I can hardly handle that.

119
00:04:58,740 --> 00:05:00,260
Now this is knucklehead talk.

120
00:05:00,260 --> 00:05:01,340
I'm not going to bite it.

121
00:05:01,340 --> 00:05:02,860
You know, you can't give me gravy

122
00:05:02,860 --> 00:05:06,180
and tell me it's jelly because gravy ain't sweet, is it, Jim?

123
00:05:06,180 --> 00:05:07,020
Oh, thanks.

124
00:05:07,020 --> 00:05:08,220
Michael?

125
00:05:08,220 --> 00:05:09,420
Forget the question.

126
00:05:09,420 --> 00:05:11,860
I think one of you should return to sales,

127
00:05:11,860 --> 00:05:13,900
and the other one will be manager.

128
00:05:13,900 --> 00:05:17,020
I humbly accept the management position.

129
00:05:17,020 --> 00:05:18,820
Why would you just automatically get it?

130
00:05:18,820 --> 00:05:20,940
Because, well, Jim, where I'm from,

131
00:05:20,940 --> 00:05:23,420
there are two types of folk, those who ain't,

132
00:05:23,420 --> 00:05:26,540
and those who are knee-high on a grasshopper.

133
00:05:26,540 --> 00:05:29,060
Which type ain't you ain't?

134
00:05:29,060 --> 00:05:31,660
Y'all come back now.

135
00:05:31,660 --> 00:05:33,020
Do you even know what that means?

136
00:05:33,020 --> 00:05:33,780
Yes.

137
00:05:33,780 --> 00:05:37,140
Well, I'm going to let this marinate so you can go.

138
00:05:37,140 --> 00:05:37,980
You can go on.

139
00:05:37,980 --> 00:05:38,480
Yep.

140
00:05:38,480 --> 00:05:39,260
All right.

141
00:05:39,260 --> 00:05:40,820
Shoot.

142
00:05:40,820 --> 00:05:43,260
I'm Jolene Bennett, Joe for short.

143
00:05:43,260 --> 00:05:45,740
I'm a breast cancer survivor, close personal friends

144
00:05:45,740 --> 00:05:47,700
with Nancy Pelosi and Truman Capote,

145
00:05:47,700 --> 00:05:49,780
and I slept with three of the same guys.

146
00:05:49,780 --> 00:05:52,420
When I was a little girl, I was terrified to fly,

147
00:05:52,420 --> 00:05:54,420
and now I have my own pilot's license.

148
00:05:54,420 --> 00:05:57,460
I am CEO of Sabre International, and I sell the best damn

149
00:05:57,460 --> 00:06:00,220
printers and all in one machine Korea can make.

150
00:06:00,220 --> 00:06:01,420
Pleased to meet you.

151
00:06:01,420 --> 00:06:02,660
Whoa, traffic jam.

152
00:06:02,660 --> 00:06:04,420
Uh-oh, traffic jam on Route 3.

153
00:06:04,420 --> 00:06:05,300
Beep, beep.

154
00:06:05,300 --> 00:06:06,100
Beep, beep.

155
00:06:06,100 --> 00:06:07,780
20 people dead in a pile up.

156
00:06:07,780 --> 00:06:11,060
There's blood everywhere.

157
00:06:11,060 --> 00:06:12,700
I got you a Valentine's card.

158
00:06:12,700 --> 00:06:13,220
You did?

159
00:06:13,220 --> 00:06:15,580
Yeah.

160
00:06:15,620 --> 00:06:17,140
Oh, a bird and a dog.

161
00:06:17,140 --> 00:06:19,020
Yeah, well, it's Snoopy and Woodstock.

162
00:06:19,020 --> 00:06:20,500
You named them?

163
00:06:20,500 --> 00:06:21,940
Charles Schultz did.

164
00:06:21,940 --> 00:06:23,940
I thought it was relevant because I got you all those

165
00:06:23,940 --> 00:06:25,620
birds for Christmas, remember?

166
00:06:25,620 --> 00:06:27,780
Yeah, I do remember.

167
00:06:27,780 --> 00:06:29,380
Oh, they love each other.

168
00:06:29,380 --> 00:06:30,180
Oh, look at that.

169
00:06:30,180 --> 00:06:31,140
They sure do.

170
00:06:31,140 --> 00:06:32,660
I hadn't noticed.

171
00:06:32,660 --> 00:06:34,140
Smells really good, too.

172
00:06:34,140 --> 00:06:35,660
Yeah, it's Roger Petter for men.

173
00:06:35,660 --> 00:06:37,140
I sprayed some in there.

174
00:06:37,140 --> 00:06:39,020
Andy, whoa.

175
00:06:39,020 --> 00:06:40,100
Thank you very much.

176
00:06:40,100 --> 00:06:42,180
It's got fair bones in it.

177
00:06:42,180 --> 00:06:43,180
Hey.

178
00:06:43,180 --> 00:06:44,380
Hi.

179
00:06:44,380 --> 00:06:46,740
Just choosing seats, not getting married.

180
00:06:46,740 --> 00:06:48,660
Chop, chop, little onion.

181
00:06:48,660 --> 00:06:50,660
Joe, there's books in my chair.

182
00:06:50,660 --> 00:06:51,940
That's right, darling.

183
00:06:51,940 --> 00:06:55,380
Now you're the proud new owner of a Sabre handbook

184
00:06:55,380 --> 00:06:57,180
and my autobiography.

185
00:06:57,180 --> 00:06:59,740
Why is it called Take a Good Look?

186
00:06:59,740 --> 00:07:03,100
I was 26 years old, working at Kodak.

187
00:07:03,100 --> 00:07:05,300
It was my first job after Vanderbilt.

188
00:07:05,300 --> 00:07:06,300
It was very exciting.

189
00:07:06,300 --> 00:07:07,740
I took it very seriously.

190
00:07:07,740 --> 00:07:10,780
But I wasn't afforded the same amount of respect

191
00:07:10,780 --> 00:07:12,860
that the rest of the board enjoyed.

192
00:07:12,860 --> 00:07:15,180
One day, I'd headed up to here.

193
00:07:15,180 --> 00:07:17,300
And I strode into the boardroom, wearing nothing

194
00:07:17,300 --> 00:07:20,300
but a pair of spiked heels, a lace push-up bra,

195
00:07:20,300 --> 00:07:23,380
and matching lace panties.

196
00:07:23,380 --> 00:07:24,660
And I took my seat.

197
00:07:24,660 --> 00:07:25,980
And I looked around at all of them.

198
00:07:25,980 --> 00:07:30,020
And I said, gentlemen, if this is all you see,

199
00:07:30,020 --> 00:07:33,180
then take a good look.

200
00:07:33,180 --> 00:07:35,580
As a male manager, I would have never done that to you.

201
00:07:35,580 --> 00:07:40,820
I am nothing if not not sexist.

202
00:07:40,860 --> 00:07:43,020
That's setting the bar a little low, isn't it?

203
00:07:43,020 --> 00:07:45,820
The only time I set the bar low is for limbo.

204
00:07:45,820 --> 00:07:47,140
I can see it on your faces.

205
00:07:47,140 --> 00:07:48,420
I mean, what's going on now?

206
00:07:48,420 --> 00:07:50,900
I mean, who owns Dunder Mifflin, right?

207
00:07:50,900 --> 00:07:52,820
I mean, Sabre?

208
00:07:52,820 --> 00:07:53,940
What's that?

209
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:58,180
Some company we never heard of from down in Tallahassee?

210
00:07:58,180 --> 00:07:59,500
Where is that?

211
00:07:59,500 --> 00:08:00,620
Near Mars?

212
00:08:00,620 --> 00:08:01,700
No, we know.

213
00:08:01,700 --> 00:08:02,820
Texas?

214
00:08:02,820 --> 00:08:05,340
Now, Dunder Mifflin has an arms reach

215
00:08:05,340 --> 00:08:08,100
and all these small businesses all over the Northeast.

216
00:08:08,100 --> 00:08:10,860
And now we're going to take that arm

217
00:08:10,860 --> 00:08:15,380
and we're going to start selling printers.

218
00:08:15,380 --> 00:08:16,780
I could manage my way around that.

219
00:08:16,780 --> 00:08:18,740
They're the easiest to use printers in the market.

220
00:08:18,740 --> 00:08:21,860
I will try to manage my excitement.

221
00:08:21,860 --> 00:08:24,420
It seems like Joe feels that there might be one too

222
00:08:24,420 --> 00:08:26,580
many managers around here.

223
00:08:26,580 --> 00:08:28,580
And Michael's response seems to be to use the word

224
00:08:28,580 --> 00:08:31,540
manage as often as possible.

225
00:08:31,540 --> 00:08:34,700
I have been saying the word manager a lot.

226
00:08:34,700 --> 00:08:39,420
So whenever Joe thinks manager, she thinks of me.

227
00:08:39,420 --> 00:08:41,420
Camel cigarettes did the same thing with Joe Camel

228
00:08:41,420 --> 00:08:43,420
by making him look like a penis.

229
00:08:43,420 --> 00:08:46,260
I can't even go near a cigarette now

230
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:49,460
without thinking of a penis and vice versa.

231
00:08:49,460 --> 00:08:50,620
I think that's it.

232
00:08:50,620 --> 00:08:52,340
So we're all good.

233
00:08:52,340 --> 00:08:53,220
Thanks, y'all.

234
00:08:57,060 --> 00:09:01,700
When I was a kid, I used to try to work in ice cream

235
00:09:01,700 --> 00:09:04,260
into every conversation I had with my mother

236
00:09:04,260 --> 00:09:06,220
so she would get me ice cream.

237
00:09:06,220 --> 00:09:10,220
And then one day she said, Michael,

238
00:09:10,220 --> 00:09:14,420
if you don't stop saying ice cream, I am going to kill you.

239
00:09:14,420 --> 00:09:16,580
And then she felt so bad that she went out

240
00:09:16,580 --> 00:09:18,300
and got me ice cream.

241
00:09:18,300 --> 00:09:20,100
So it's a pretty effective strategy.

242
00:09:25,060 --> 00:09:25,900
Oh my God.

243
00:09:27,020 --> 00:09:28,580
I guess Andy likes me.

244
00:09:28,580 --> 00:09:30,780
I never thought of him in that way.

245
00:09:30,780 --> 00:09:32,620
But I guess in most romantic comedies,

246
00:09:32,620 --> 00:09:33,780
the guy you're supposed to be with

247
00:09:33,780 --> 00:09:35,980
is the one that you never thought of in that way.

248
00:09:35,980 --> 00:09:37,220
You might have even thought he was annoying

249
00:09:37,220 --> 00:09:38,620
or possibly homosexual.

250
00:09:40,100 --> 00:09:41,580
So check this out.

251
00:09:41,580 --> 00:09:42,940
According to the handbook,

252
00:09:42,940 --> 00:09:45,740
you could make more money as a salesman than as a manager.

253
00:09:45,740 --> 00:09:47,860
They have all these incentive programs.

254
00:09:47,860 --> 00:09:49,500
I ran your numbers from last year.

255
00:09:49,500 --> 00:09:51,380
This is way more than I make now.

256
00:09:51,380 --> 00:09:53,660
I don't think I'm gonna miss being manager.

257
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:55,420
You know, some people say they're not in it for the money.

258
00:09:55,420 --> 00:09:57,420
Well, with all due respect to this job,

259
00:09:57,420 --> 00:09:59,660
I think I'm definitely in it for the money.

260
00:09:59,660 --> 00:10:01,220
And quite honestly, the women.

261
00:10:01,380 --> 00:10:02,660
Hey, got a second?

262
00:10:02,660 --> 00:10:03,500
Sure.

263
00:10:03,500 --> 00:10:04,340
All right.

264
00:10:04,340 --> 00:10:05,180
What are you here to tell me

265
00:10:05,180 --> 00:10:06,820
that you think I would be a better manager

266
00:10:06,820 --> 00:10:09,020
and that you are sorry for being such a jerk?
